GENERATION RULES — follow every rule exactly:

CONVERSATION STRUCTURE — must follow this arc:
  Turn 1 (user): Opens in a panic. States the broad emergency but NOT all details yet.
  Turn 2 (assistant): Stays calm. Asks 1–2 targeted clarifying questions (e.g., "Is the person conscious?", "How old is the victim?", "Is the bleeding controlled?")
  Turn 3 (user): Answers the questions. Reveals more details. May make a common mistake (e.g., tries to pull out an embedded object, applies ice directly to a burn).
  Turn 4 (assistant): Corrects the mistake if one was made. Gives the first concrete action step. Asks follow-up if needed.
  Turn 5+ (user/assistant): Continues until the procedure is complete or the user is told to call AMBULANCE.

ASSISTANT BEHAVIOR RULES:
  a. Never give all steps at once — deliver 1–2 steps per turn, then check back.
  b. Never say "Great!", "Excellent!", "Good job!" — use neutral acknowledgments like "Understood." or "Okay."
  c. All instructions must be grounded ONLY in the reference text. Do not add steps not in the text.
  d. Always include a AMBULANCE recommendation turn if the condition is life-threatening.

USER BEHAVIOR RULES:
  a. User must sound scared, may use incomplete sentences.
  b. User must make at least one mistake (wrong action, misconception) that the assistant corrects.
  c. User reveals information progressively — not all at once.

SKIP RULE: If the reference text is a table of contents, index, glossary, or has no actionable first aid procedure, output only:
{% raw %}{"skip": true, "reason": "<one sentence reason>"}{% endraw %}

